Assessment of Fixes
V018 delivery wiring — is it actually good?

Yes. The design is correct:

The notify task is AFTER the scan (correct dependency)
Auto-resume only if the integration exists (graceful degradation)
The integration itself (holding the webhook secret) correctly stays outside git in webhook_delivery.sql
Digest uses SYSTEM$SEND_SNOWFLAKE_NOTIFICATION with a guarded exception — the right Snowflake-native mechanism
The one-time integration setup is still manual (as it must be — secrets don't belong in migrations)
The separation is: what to notify (V018, in git) vs where to send (webhook_delivery.sql, manual one-time). That's the correct split.

Governance weights — done correctly?

Yes. Mirrors the platform score pattern exactly: DEFAULT_GOV_WEIGHTS dict → resolve_gov_weights(settings) → pass to governance_drift(inputs, weights). Operators can now tune GOV_PTS_MFA_GAP, GOV_PTS_EXPIRED_CRED, etc. via SETTINGS.

Timeline tiering — does it solve the problem?

Mostly. The 48h/recent window keeps the "mid-incident I need fresh data" use case. The 7d/historical window (1h cache) protects against the expensive three-source join on every page load. The radio toggle is appropriate UX. Minor nitpick: the default should be "48h" (the DBA opening Control Room during an incident wants fresh, not cached).

