What I Genuinely Dislike (Round 4)
The list is now short and mostly architectural:

String-interpolated SQL is still the #1 technical debt. Four rounds and it hasn't moved. I understand why — it's a refactor that touches every file in app/data/, has no user-visible benefit, and risks introducing bugs. But it remains the single biggest security and maintainability concern. If this app ever gets a pen test, this is finding #1.

The closed-loop is still open. You now have: detect (alert scan) → notify (webhook) → investigate (timeline + drill) → remediate (playbooks exist) → verify (savings ledger). But the human still manually connects each step. The "one-click from alert to approved remediation to verified saving" workflow doesn't exist as a continuous flow. Each piece works individually; the seams between them are still manual page navigation.

No PagerDuty/Slack-native delivery. SYSTEM$SEND_SNOWFLAKE_NOTIFICATION with a webhook integration is good, but the webhook target is a single URL. Enterprise on-call expects: CRITICAL → PagerDuty (wakes someone up) vs HIGH → Slack channel (team sees it in the morning). The ALERT_ROUTES table exists for per-family routing, but SP_NOTIFY_WEBHOOK appears to send everything through one integration. Severity-based routing to different endpoints would be the next level.

The app cannot tell you its own ROI. After 4 rounds, it detects, alerts, notifies, and tracks savings — but there's no "OVERWATCH has saved X this quarter" summary for leadership. The savings ledger has the data. A single KPI on the Brief ("Verified savings this quarter: X") would close the loop on executive justification for the tool's existence.

Net Assessment
The trajectory from R1 to R4: 68 → 76 → 80 → 83. Each round addresses the most critical open finding with an architecturally sound fix. The author's response pattern is notable: no cosmetic shortcuts, no partial fixes, no "we'll address it later" deferrals. Each criticism gets a proper solution or a deliberate documented decision not to fix it.

The delivery wiring in V018 closes the last fundamental gap. The app now:

Detects problems (26 rules, per-rule isolation)
Explains them (Cortex-grounded anomaly hypotheses)
Notifies humans (webhook delivery, chained after scan)
Provides investigation tools (incident timeline, ±30min drill)
Offers remediation (playbooks, generated SQL)
Verifies outcomes (savings ledger)
That's a complete monitoring system, not a dashboard.

"If I had 40 hours right now?"

Build the closed-loop remediation page (20h) — single workflow from alert to approved fix to verification.
Add ROI KPI to Brief: "Verified savings this quarter" (4h).
Refactor app/data/ to use parameterized queries (16h) — eliminate the security debt.
"What would turn this into an elite platform?"

Severity-based routing (CRITICAL → PagerDuty, HIGH → Slack, MEDIUM → email digest), the closed-loop workflow, multi-account org aggregation, Native App packaging for Marketplace distribution, and a proper design system refresh. At 83/100 with delivery wired in, the remaining distance is product polish and scale — not architecture.
